Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 countries of the eurozone, the inflation rate was higher than expected in November – after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was registered, as reported by the EU’s statistical office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are expected to be as low as 3%, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the leitzsins. In its opinion, the interest rate cut would favor the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment.
The ECB strives to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in a quandary: inflation must be “agreed” in order to rule out the need for action later on.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in November in Germany reached a twelve-year record high; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Rising food and energy prices are responsible for the rise in inflation in the eurozone.
MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and soybean prices also hit a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in prices for cooking oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year – last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation is expected to rise from 2.1 per cent in 2008 to 2.5 per cent, but it is expected to decline to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
Analysts expect a 3 percent inflation rate over the next 3-4 months, but estimate the annual average rate at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup's Government Crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of Fidesz supporters has grown considerably until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while approval for the socialists, according to Gallup, has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent.
In the case of party- loyal voters, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: More than two thirds (71 percent) are opposed to a fifth (20 percent) of the support for the MSZP.
According to the survey, the MDF and the SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry barrier: they come to two percent of the total population.
The number of party voters in both camps has grown by one percent.
Compared to the last low, general economic sentiment has continued to deteriorate – never before has the proportion of those who rate the country’s economic situation as “extremely bad” been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it “pretty bad”.
After more hopeful prospects in the spring and summer, families see the change in their financial situation once again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only a tenth of them expect an improvement.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents – a historic high – rated the Prime Minister’s work as “rather bad than right.”
Thirteen percent of the respondents have great confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcs<0xC3><0xA1>ny in general, while the proportion of supporters for Viktor Orb<0xC3><0xA1>n accounts for 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% distrust of the party leader of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be managed without a change of government.
After the riots last October, 35% had voted in favour of the government and the head of government remaining, but today this share amounts to only 20%, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent responded that they “participate with certainty” and another 20 percent would “probably” cast their vote.
By comparison, if the parliamentary elections were held this Sunday, only 55 percent would go to the polls "with certainty", another 15 percent consider their participation to be "probable". Given these trends, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital daily allowance.
In turn, the proportions of opponents of study, practice and hospital fees would be as high as 81, 84 and 89 percent, respectively.
Auchan most expensive, Tesco increased by almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trading area have also this year maintained the average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that this year there was no increase in VAT.
Articles by Napi Gazdas<0xC3><0xA1>g
In the Budaörs trade triangle, the price of the usual Christmas basket of the "Napi" has also increased by 16 percent this year, but price increases of over 1,000 HUF were registered in all hypermarkets.
After prices in the food markets “galopated” last December, the rate of inflation has not been drastic compared to the already high, earlier level.
However, it is certainly dissuasive to consumers that what they had paid for last year far below HUF 9,000 is not even available this year for HUF 10,000.
The price of the "Napi" basket exceeded the magic 10,000 HUF limit by at least 91 HUF in the markets studied.
The highest price was 10,573 HUF.
(In 6800, the price was 6,800 HUF.)
The prices for unicum and live fish remained almost at the previous year’s level, while the prices for turkey breast fillets, nut and poppy seeds rose sharply.
Prices for flour and bread corresponded to the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary, but at Auchan there were 1kg of bread rolls for 139 forints.
There was no competitive price drop below 200 forints.
Also surprising here was the price of a two liter Coca-Cola deposit bottle of under 200 forints, so the drink including deposit cost only 257 HUF.
Nevertheless, this year in the "Napi" shopping cart comparison Auchan scored the most expensive, and Cora the cheapest.
Our calculations have shown that Cora has increased the prices in the "Napi" shopping cart compared to the Christmas prices last year by 15 percent, while Tesco and Auchan have each increased by 18 percent.
The difference between last year’s cheapest shopping basket and this year’s most expensive was 12%, while the increase between last year’s cheapest shopping basket and this year’s most expensive one was 21%.
The average price increase was 1,480.00 HUF.
The average price increase was still 1,206.00 forints in the previous year, but the VAT increase was noticeable in the prices at last Christmas.
It is precisely this process that has hit the trade badly: apparently the department stores could not really decide which price range to apply to the individual articles, since the effects of the price increase on consumer behavior were unpredictable.
(If the trader is planning a product’s circulation speed poorly, he may drop by substantial profits in the price range, which depends on the traffic intensity.)
Due to VAT, the price of the "Napi" basket last year was so radical that the most expensive basket exceeded the value of 2006 by 1720 forints, whereas the price difference for the cheapest basket was only 844 forints.
This year, such extremes were not observed, as the most expensive basket cost 1,630.00 forints more than last year, and even the cheapest one saw a price increase of 1,284.00 forints.
Compared to the last two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic price increase, the price of daily consumables in the hypermarkets has risen by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, in turn, does not necessarily confirm the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary: for some basic foodstuffs, the Statistical Office found a more than 30% increase in the price over the 12-month period.
So in addition to flour, also with eggs.)
However, if you take a look at the "Napi" shopping cart, this seems almost impossible with the latter, since the price level of the product, which was already expensive in the previous year, has risen by barely more than 10 percent even in the worst case.
Obviously flour suppliers are in a stronger position than the egg suppliers - after all, they were able to pass the drastic price increase on to the multinationals.
In the golden trade triangle, hypermarkets do not complain; good years are constantly being reported.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores no longer even look at the prices.
Large quantities are purchased from everything, durable food goes over the counter in pallets.
Wednesday morning there were endless queues at the cash desk in all three department stores when suddenly the number of customers exploded.
However, the country is reported to have a lower customer frequency, so many multinationals complain to the pollsters that they could not even reach the planned turnover, not only for food, but also for sustainable consumer goods.
In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overload of the staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the containment of infections, according to the lead doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos hospital, an MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The victim of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly afterwards the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not yet been performed because of the bacterium that is still in the patient’s body.
By December 10 of this year, 1094 infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens had been reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System from hospitals, according to the lead physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about one-third of people in its nose without it causing disease.
SA-related infections (such as strep throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are over-dosed or used improperly, the well-responsive bacteria develop into antibiotic-resistant bacteria that quickly spread under appropriate conditions in hospitals.
Especially in patients with weakened or permanently malfunctioning immune systems, but also in older patients or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday life in the hospital.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA just does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wear rubber gloves and masks during the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, patients are examined for MRSA, but an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rarely
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for curbing the emergence or spread of the multidrug-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is predominantly found in hospitals and retirement homes, hospitals should examine the admitted patients and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
However, microbiological sampling is not so common in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no grants from the state health insurance for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to light if the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological examinations are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Among the outpatient or primary care patients, microbiological sampling is even rarer, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Savings are made with disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by caregivers.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in this area in the hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient.
In fact, the rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are just next to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the less financially well-off hospitals, it even happens that there are savings in disinfectants, there are few carers, many patients - all factors that almost favor the development of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes enormous costs to health insurance companies, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
After initial indications, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made prevention of the emergence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
