Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all of Europe is paying attention to the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who buys in the still cheapest market of the EU, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An Analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is without a doubt the most sought-after pavement for property purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Among the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea Albena, the "gold coast", the "sun coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nesebar the Renner, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior will also attract investors sooner or later, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the very favorable area of Ruse has more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office space offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfers’ paradises, and thus attracting tourists in addition to the summer and winter seasons as well as in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying in a big way, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also striving to change their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down either buy revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or rundown houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connection and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are decisive for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group is made up of business people who invest with the aim of increasing value in the medium to long term.
However, real estate in the capital is constantly becoming more expensive, due to the constantly growing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the last five years there has been an annual increase of 21 percent.
The price increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
As Environment Minister G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will come to an end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the expiry of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a heated debate between developed and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate on concrete figures, but would be willing to cut greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
The other big question of the conference is whether the developed countries are willing to support the developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on support for developing countries has also been reached.
The Adaptation Fund, which is subordinated to the Kyoto Protocol, is to be managed by a 16-member Council, presumably at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as stated in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured against 1990 levels), whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" is achieved successfully, and the Union would even be willing to push for a 30% reduction if other major industrialised countries of the world, or developing countries, are also willing to meet their commitments to the best of their ability and responsibly.
G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor stressed that the objective of the states that had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its then 15 member states, had already committed to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, as can be read in the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
The commitment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be ready within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction project defined in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed by a new, international emission reduction system, the importance of which the IPCC, the international scientific climate change committee awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, has also highlighted in its latest report.
This would delay emission reduction, and increase the Earth’s average temperature by more than 2°C would be inevitable, leading to extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos about operations conducted against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The images, shot with miniature cameras mounted on helmets, are checked at the Kandahar Air Force Base and then sent to London, where they are posted on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 to publish videos on Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Foreign Office (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Operation ''Afghanistan'''
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of the foreign missions.
Propaganda of this kind is almost free of charge compared to conventional television advertising, according to defence expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans Advertise with Game
But the army must also fight against amateur shots, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored shots, also make it into the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are talked about at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Incidentally, from the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos filmed in action have already been uploaded to the platform, but this "genus" has only recently been discovered by the British.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "Americas Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less life-like simulation.
