More and more forces mobilized for giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Trade Union Federation will form their coordination committee on Friday for the strike of an indefinite duration starting on Monday.
On Saturday, a large-scale protest meeting will be held, on Monday - on the day of the referendum on the Health Insurance Act - the work stoppage begins.
It is expected that there will be significant traffic disruptions due to the strike, since rail traffic will be almost completely stopped, and the Budapest public transport companies (BKV) will also strike until 1 p.m.
Details on Monday’s strike will be shared by the League of Trade Unions and the Trade Union Federation on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee will also be set up, which will be responsible for coordinating the actions on Monday.
A large-scale protest meeting will be held on Saturday, and from Monday onwards all organisations that have joined the strike will cease work indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike that began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act was not defined.
If the National Council does not adopt the health insurance law, the unions immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the law is passed, the strike committee will meet to discuss the next steps.
Due to the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that a vote on the health insurance law will only take place in the late evening hours, or even at midnight.
The strikes, which begin on Monday, will result in significant traffic disruptions: railway workers will be laid off indefinitely, most of the public transport and more than half of the Vol<0xC3><0xA1>n companies will be shut down in the morning.
At the same time, there will be motorway closures of one direction in many places.
The call for strike has been followed by numerous trade unions and civil organizations - the list of participants is constantly updated on the League website.
Some organizations announced strikes indefinitely, others are planning a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon, no agreement could be reached between the Hungarian Railways M<0xC3><0x81>V and the Free Trade Union of Railways VDSZSZ on sufficient services, although especially around the Christmas holidays more and more people are traveling by train.
According to previous reports, the BKV will strike from the start of operations until 1 p.m., at Budapest Airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the LIGA unions for electricity and heat energy will stop working for four hours, and the teachers' union, for example the Democratic Teachers' Union, have called for 2 or 2-8 hour strikes.
The Hungarian Medical Association strikes alternatingly across the country at various times, the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organization of the SZEF, the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation, holds a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraw the draft health insurance reform and submit a new conception for social discourse.
The second requirement concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due from next year.
The third requirement is that eligible professional groups have access to the early retirement system before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which belongs to the League of Trade Unions, has not accepted the offer made by the Ministry of Transport concerning the secondary lines and is now calling for a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to Political Capital’s Risk Analysing Division, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded this August with the support of the “Movement for a Better Hungary”, have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things, that, in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "intensification of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsies and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at the provocation of such a dispute, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of the political leaders: "Persons of public life have left the discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical political groups, who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition."
It is thought that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favor extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention paid to them by the domestic and foreign media, “have seriously damaged Hungary’s image abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity.”
We remember that since the autumn of 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been continuously on the upswing, so that since the summer of 2007, several organizations called "national self-defense associations" have been founded.
“These groups have in common that they each define themselves as a civilian organization, while openly bragging about preparing their members for – sometimes armed – defence tasks (catastrophe protection, national defence, law enforcement), citing the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state itself,” it said.
And again: all this is done according to the method that tries to disguise various political aspirations as a bourgeois initiative based on the political and party disillusionment of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association therefore serve not only to circumvent legal hurdles that could arise in the course of registration in court - it is also a political strategy.
