Holidays are not everywhere
In Hungary, holidays are regulated exactly by law, so the practice of re-disposing the working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the coming year will give us fewer such days.
Also in the EU and in America one understands something else by "holidays".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and non-working days.
Non-working days are mostly church holidays, or are related to significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter just so that the New Year celebrations can rest.
In the whole year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The national holidays are the 15th of March, which commemorates the Revolution of 1848, and the 23rd of October, the anniversary of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20, the founding of the state, on May 1 the work is celebrated, on November 1 and 2 we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of “workday shift” has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we work very well on the Saturdays before, or have to go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be worked out, has for many years been determined by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and recipients, public employees and civil servants alike.
Only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on public holidays, are excluded.
This year, the work order is only confused by the holidays at the end of the year: From December 24th, life in this country will officially stand still, since most take time off for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or take the specially cancelled vacation.
Next year, more holidays fall in the middle of the week, or the end of the week, so that there will be fewer re-dispositions in the working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday April 26th will be a working day so that Friday May 2nd can be a day of rest.
The second re-disposition is related to the holiday on 23 October: on Saturday, 18 October, you will have to finish the Friday, 24 October in advance.
The end of the year, however, will be completely marked by the holidays, after everything will stop from December 24, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six Dissuasive Little Things to Annoy Workmates
E-mails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we no longer notice: They bring "color" into everyday life in the workplace.
The only question is whether to get used to these small inconveniences, or to better face the challenge and try to avoid these misunderstood, for other annoying situations consciously.
Tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone from the marketing department called" - says a colleague.
That you missed a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it by perhaps calling the marketing department and confessing repentantly that you forgot to line the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, the case is dismissed with an apology.
Before you get caught up in embarrassing excuses, you should think about how you can give your colleagues really unpleasant moments and try to avoid these situations consciously.
Borrow something that doesn’t belong to you?
There’s hardly anything more annoying than reaching for a document, office accessories, or the phone, but it’s not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague’s desk?
Without questions, one should not borrow anything from colleagues, because they are rightly upset when they find that something has gone away.
So, don't put envelopes or post-it from the office in your pocket, because it could hit you: no more if you really need it.
Talk about the private lives of your colleagues?
There is no effective means of stopping a gossip that has already been put into the world.
Who did what with whom?
Where and why?
One should not tie the information (or assumptions) about the private lives of colleagues to everyone's nose if possible!
And if someone opens up and reveals his innermost secret to us, we should not abuse this trust!
It is best to remain silent like a grave, instead of aligning those who are not present at the moment, even if others know about the problems of the colleague.
Reported sick for no reason?
When you call the office to report sick, citing excruciating headaches, because you are feeling uncomfortable, or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: your own work, undeliverable tasks, projects with fixed deadlines must now be done by your colleagues instead of yourself.
Don’t play bad with your colleagues.
If you already know the day before that you will not make it to the office the next day, or that something could interfere, which is why you have to stay at home, you should report it in time, so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
Call me, call me, call me
One is just deepened in his work, but is suddenly disturbed by the loud giggles of the colleagues?
Unintentionally listening to a phone call that you shouldn’t have heard?
One should not annoy colleagues with humming, singing, loud conversations (which one carries over their heads), trampling, constant scolding or nagging.
All of this can be very disruptive, even if they are not particularly engrossed in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Are the others always to blame?
If a project is not completed on time, you have forgotten to send an important letter or important messages, you should not seek the guilt of your own forgetfulness from others!
If possible, you should not talk yourself out of the chaos in the office or the loud colleagues!
It is best to admit your mistakes and apologize if others have been affected.
The question of how to make up for the mistake, or make up for the missed one, is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like home?
Training pants and slacks: Comfortable for at home, but has not lost anything in the office!
Not even then should you dress so casually, if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress appropriately in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
