The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
For example, more than $100 billion will reach the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, the banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to lend each other money.
For example, the U.S. Fed sends $40 billion at auction, while another 24 make it easy for the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time, after the attacks of 11 September, that the central banks of the individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to ward off or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties facing the economy, i.e. the increasing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," wrote in a report for his clients Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group.
“Coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the U.S. from 65% to about 50%,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unserved loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect further losses of billions.
“The central banks must have been really afraid of what could still be done when they decided to do so,” Kieran Davies, ABN Amro’s chief economist, said in a statement.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he continued.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
That would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into a recession, possibly affecting economic growth around the world.
The central banks have decided to do so after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank interest rate used to lend money between banks.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid to lend each other money, even though the central banks of the US, Canada and the UK had lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
