The integration of Slovak students in British schools is not successful
In British schools, the number of children from Eastern European countries is increasing, causing fears among locals about the further development of the local school system.
So far, the integration of Eastern Europeans has encountered a number of obstacles.
British schools are even finding cases where disputes between the immigrants and the children of the original residents are increasing in violence.
The problem with the integration of children from Eastern Europe into British schools is aptly illustrated by the case of North Kent, where disputes between locals and Slovak immigrants are gradually increasing.
Disputes, harassment and robberies among students have spread to relationships between parents.
The situation has already developed to such an extent that the police in Chatham arrested a Slovak woman who had beaten a ten-year-old boy with an iron bar.
The accused defended himself by saying that the boy had insulted her with racist insults.
The police also had to intervene after an attack by two minor girls on a Slovak immigrant.
The girls allegedly made racist remarks to the man and pelted him with stones.
"When we went home, a boy climbed on a bushling and spat on us.
When I told him to stop, he threw apples and pears at us and then exposed his buttocks," a mother of Slovak students described another unpleasant incident to The Times.
Complaints come from both sides.
One of the locals even described the dispute with the immigrants from Eastern Europe as a struggle for survival.
The above cases testify that the mood between locals and immigrants in British schools is becoming more and more tense.
In the UK, 70,000 Slovaks are registered to come here for work.
Around 30,000 Slovak students attend British schools.
Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, it will be fulfilled if you choose only the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palm trees and All Inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this to an excessive extent.
But there is much more to be found on one island, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a storehouse or transit warehouse of treasures that the Spaniards had stolen in America and then transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the leaders of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the US (especially during the Prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were a.o.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
High-rise buildings grew in Havana, cars drove over the wide boulevards, which were among the cult symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Coj<0xC3><0xAD>mar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
On the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana you can also leave your autograph.
At the bar in the Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails according to your wishes.
And the cult cars of the fifties are still driving around in Havana today, because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
Havana, especially its oldest part, may be very run down, nowhere can you find so many wonderful colonial sights in the vicinity as here.
Other places are currently being cleaned out, for example Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have been created not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holgu<0xC3><0xAD>n and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a marotte that is unique in the world and above all attracts railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-driven narrow-gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see cute and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have been in the museum elsewhere for a long time.
Excursion destinations
The most important places do not leave out the majority of visitors to Cuba.
So you no longer have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail.
It is worth noting that there is a museum in the aforementioned Hemingway estate, which should not be missed by anyone who likes this writer.
The Vi<0xC3><0xB1>ales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities fertile soil accumulated, through which even weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet it if you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Fame and wealth brought her the trade of slaves and sugar.
The wealth was embodied in the pretty beauty of the small town.
The Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that there was no road there in the fifties of the last century that would have connected the area to the rest of the country.
This isolation helped it go unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was happy that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, then it is worth to look at interesting places in the area, such as Playa Anc<0xC3><0xB3>n beach or the "Valley of sugar factories".
In the evening you should go to the Casa de la M<0xC3><0xBA>sica, which revives after dark, and where the music does not remain silent until morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful on the island.
Surely this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads, which lead from Guant<0xC3><0xA1>namo, have to overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is hardly touched by human intervention.
This eastern outpost of Cuba was included by UNESCO in its World Heritage List thanks to its untouched nature.
The best chocolate is made there, in the church you can see the Columbus cross (in fact it was made about a hundred years after Columbus’s voyages), and from the hill where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, several table mountains can be seen, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra Mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, you could write many pages about all this.
As they say, it’s better to see with your own eyes.
Allies in Afghanistan are passive, Americans claim.
According to the United States, too few soldiers and the lack of necessary equipment influence the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
NATO should, in the words of Defense Secretary Robert Gates, draw up a concrete plan for the next few years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going according to their ideas, the representatives of the countries that have stationed units in the south of the country agreed on this in Edinburgh, Scotland.
In addition to the growing resistance from the Taliban, the eight participating states are also discussing further coordination plans among the allies.
While the United States, through its Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, called on NATO units to be more active, Britain sees the priority in strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and in intensifying development aid.
"A forward development is noticeable in Afghanistan, but military power can only be part of the solution.
Another part is to allow residents to begin to develop the economy and security themselves," British Defence Secretary Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
The activity of the Afghan insurgents has reached the highest level in five years, according to the American army.
The number of violent acts has increased by 27 percent compared to the previous year, and even by sixty percent in the southern province of Helmand.
The NATO countries have deployed about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, about a quarter of them in southern territory.
According to the United States, however, the allies have reached an absolute limit when it comes to the organization and equipment of the units.
Specifically, they are calling for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train the Afghan units.
"We will have to seriously think about the concrete goals for the next period and the way we can achieve them," Gates said.
NATO Secretary General Jaap de Hoop said the same.
"I am not pleased with what we have available on land and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about ninety percent of the soldiers and equipment we need, and that's too little," De Hoop told Reuters at the conclusion of three-day talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
Who is passive
In recent months, there has also been a dispute among the countries involved as to whether all allies in Afghanistan are doing their best.
Germany, for example, has been criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans are relatively numerous in Afghanistan.
However, they are stationed in areas where there is only a minimum of violence and the fighting requirements for them are not as high as for us in the southern and eastern part of the country," Gates said.
The British tabloid Sun called the German soldiers lazy this week.
"Afghan non-stars exposed: The Germans are making games while our boys are fighting," wrote the "Sun" in a post supplemented by photos of German soldiers playing table tennis.
The German Bild newspaper counterattacked and printed a picture of a British unit at a rugby match in the southern part of Afghanistan.
Public debt will rise to a trillion in 2009
Each Czech has a national debt of 84,000 kroner.
Total debt increased to 842.7 billion kroner by the end of September.
The government had planned to indebted itself to 159.2 billion cones this year.
At the beginning of December, however, the ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion, thanks to the better development of the state budget policy.
The government debt of the Czech Republic rose to 842.7 billion kroner by the end of September.
Within the first nine months of this year, they rose by 40.2 billion.
Since June, however, they have fallen by 13.4 billion.
The Ministry of Finance confirmed its information on the government debt from the beginning of October.
Each Czech has a debt of 84,000 kroner.
Over the entire past year, the state was indebted by more than 111 billion kroner.
“Until now, it seems that thanks to the lower deficit for the coming year, we may not exceed the limit of one trillion crowns until 2009.
Next year, the debt should be between 900 billion and a trillion kroner," David Marek, an analyst at Patria Finance, told iHNed.cz.
Similarly, Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Pikora, analyst at Next Finance, said: “To exceed one trillion we could come in the course of 2009.
When exactly depends on the next budget, which we do not know yet.
If it turns out that the situation on the political stage is changing, and politicians should be willing to save more, it could take until 2010.
But I do not expect such a change," he remarked.
Debts are growing
The national debt comes from the debts of the state government and comes mainly from the accumulation of deficits of the state budget.
The government debt is financed by treasury bonds, government bonds, direct bonds or, for example, bonds issued by the European Investment Bank.
The domestic national debt has now risen to 719.4 billion kroner this year.
The foreign debt of the state has now increased by 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable government debt reached 803.3 billion kroner at the end of September and has fallen by 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of government debt rose to 6.5 years.
“Over the year, total debt increased by 13 percent from the first to the third quarter, which is really a lot given how well the economy is doing.
It is interesting to note that the growth is mainly in the debt securities, where the increase is 20 percent.
It’s bad that debt is rising, but on the other hand it shows that you can do something even before the pension reform comes,” Pikora said.
Better than expected
The financing strategy and management of the government debt for 2007 show that the government had planned for this year to take in 159.2 billion kroner.
At the beginning of December, however, the Ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion kroner thanks to the better development of the state budget policy.
This amount is mainly due to the government budget deficit, which will apparently reach 76 billion kroner this year instead of the estimated 91.3 billion.
In addition, the maximum budget allocated to the Consolidation Agency is 13.3 billion kroner, a ten-billion reserve to pay pensions, the financing of government bonds worth 43 billion kroner, and the borrowing rates at the European Investment Bank amounting to 1.8 billion kroner.
For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was presented to a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been charged with insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced to 15 days in prison and subsequently deported by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening.
The British woman has been accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old students to give the name Mahomet to a teddy bear, although any depiction of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be whipped.
After parents of students had complained to the Sudanese Ministry of Education several times, the 54-year-old elementary school teacher, who worked at Unity High School in Khartoum, was picked up at home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to pick a name for the class teddy bear.
The children propose eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, reports headmaster Robert Boules.
After all, when the class votes, 20 of 23 children choose Muhammad as their favorite first name.
Certainly, Muhammad is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all also a very common name in Sudan.
Afterwards, the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed .
The bear itself did not bear a sign with that name, but the problem is quite simple that the portrayal of the Islamic prophet is seen as an insult to Islam.
One of the Muslim colleagues at Gillian Gibbons, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, stated that he knew her well, and she never would have done anything that would have brought her too close to a religious belief, I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion this is just an innocent mistake.
An opinion shared by numerous students of the teacher, who describe them as very attentive to their students and as a person who never talks about religion in class.
Keep in mind that the first name Mohammed is also the second most common given name in the UK, for which there are 14 different spellings in English.
This first name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of reverence to the Prophet (saas) (he is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can you give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
At the last negotiating meeting in Vienna on Wednesday, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province.
At the end of the failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo ended a sixth and final discussion session Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without being able to overcome their controversies over the future status of the separatist province.
It is regrettable that the parties could not come to an agreement on the status, said the European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region is at stake, its American counterpart Frank Wilsner called on Belgrade and Pristina to meet their commitments to maintain peace and to continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No acts of violence are expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time, he added, indicating that there are quite clear tensions.
End of mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the Troika, which unites the European Union, the US and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the province, which is 90% inhabited by Albanian speakers, could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The Baden talks, near Vienna, were the sixth and last negotiating session since the Troika received a mandate from the UN last August for a new mediation.
Americans and Europeans expect their placement order to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked the approval of Kosovo’s independence at the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond that end date.
Russia has been and will remain an advocate for a negotiated solution, an amicable one, Botsane-Khartchenko said.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After Kosovo has been under the administration of the UN for eight years, the Western countries consider independence under the supervision of the EU to be the only solution with a future.
Pristina is ready to announce these unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in their favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy
Regrettably, no agreement could be reached, the president of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, announced at the hotel in Baden, where since Monday these negotiations were held the last chance.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regrets.
He added, however, that Belgrade’s proposed plan for autonomy was part of a past that led to murders and deportations.
Domino effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, was of the opinion that a compromise should always be sought, and warned the Albanian majority from Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence of the province.
Belgrade says it is particularly concerned about a “domino effect” in a region that has been weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise would be impossible, he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision be taken solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally holds a right of veto.
Kosovo's parliament will have the final say
