A heavy reminder
After being kept confidential for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed over a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be viewed until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individual and name-related, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
In May 2006, the eleven states entrusted with its administration, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to make it available to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Heikle Information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow them to conduct research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of forced laborers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were against making these name-related documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as, for example, the alleged homosexuality or the intellectual disability of some deportation victims.
The inmate lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen handle tens of thousands of personal inquiries.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in accessing Bad Arolsen.
One should not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, explained Pr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
