Congress approves MIFID’s directive, which came into force on November 1.
In parallel to the parliamentary elaboration that ended its session today with the congressional resolution in the Senate on the supplementary/amendment motions related to the project, the government published the provisions resulting from the new law with the intention of enabling the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of the congress and senate deputies, who in their negotiations and votes had the goal of establishing the best possible regulation, which ensures the safety of investors and regulates the individual entrepreneurial activities, in order to guarantee a generally efficient market.
In addition to modernising the financial markets, MIFID, which re-establishes the Securities Services Regulations, aims to improve investor protection, increase the claim to control of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive allows for the provision of financial advice to both specialised firms and to natural or legal persons, and also contributes to the establishment of new financial services firms (ESIS), the consultancy firms that join forces with investment and brokerage companies of securities.
It also increases the number of financial transaction execution systems, adding to regulated circulation markets the multilateral securities trading systems and the systems for internationalising trade orders, which would eventually compete with the current economic players.
The law obliges investment companies to disclose the main points of their company profile, the confrontation and forms of dealing with risks in the market and to register all projects carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV’s control task.
The Economic Commission of the Congress planned further changes in retrospect, whereby the decision that the securities must now be regarded as complex financial resources for the investor due to their high degree of risk, has been confirmed by the US mortgage and banking crisis.
It also took advantage of the entry into force of the Directive on the legal limitation of the areas of activity of qualified economists; 30 years after 1977, the regulation restricting the areas of activity reserved to economists was adopted.
The Senate, for its part, established new positions in the financial sector, such as that of the business mediator working on behalf of others, who does not require authorization from the CNMV and who can offer its services for the commercialization of products and for the acquisition of customers simultaneously several investment companies.
The harmonised consumer price index (CPI) rose by five-tenths in November and now stands at 4.1%.
The indicator used by Eurostat to assess the inflation rate within the European Union provides the average price development in Spain in November.
Its publication is in line with the principles of Eurostat and the European Central Bank (ECB), which aim to compare the location and quality of U.S. products by disclosing the data.
The forecast for the indicator can be prepared ahead of time by using the same approach as for the harmonised consumer price index, but at the same time using various other statistical modelling methods to estimate the information not available at the time of calculation.
However, the Spanish Statistical Office (INE) warned that the indicator identified ahead of time would only serve as a guide and would therefore not be in line with the final result to be announced on 14 December.
The consumer price index (CPI) will remain at a relatively high level
According to Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Economy and Finance Pedro Solbes, the increase in the CPI in November was a temporary development; at the same time, he assured that the price index would remain at a relatively high level in the coming months.
Nevertheless, Solbes noted in the halls of the Congress building that even if the current figure is not good, Spain’s inflation differential with the other members of the monetary union has remained more or less the same in recent years.
He also explained that there were fewer surprises in November than in the previous month, where the government did not expect such a large increase.
We expected a value of around 4%, the Minister of Economy and Finance announced in view of the forecast published today.
