New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is smoldering between Ukraine and Russia, raising the risk of Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe.
Most of Russia’s natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are routed through Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom’s imports.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks,” Ukraine’s economy minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine.”
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drove up prices dramatically.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the world’s largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve controls on criminal records for workers from outside Europe, a member of the control body said.
The recommendation of Chief Financial Controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was brought to Scotland in connection with the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish government health service has no precise idea of the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The chief financial controller investigated personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a 4x4 was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at the Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the alleged car bomb attack in Britain.
The State Health Service is expected to carry out checks prior to hiring foreign staff to ensure they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK.
