None of this means that Brown is irrevocably heading toward resignation.
Yet governments can reach a tipping point where they feel it is impossible to govern.
Neither like nor trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it’s clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he doesn’t even need to be around for long, that delay is over: public service begins to leak; cabinet ministers begin to chat; the press searches for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and aimless.
