A 2005 change in U.S. private insolvency laws led to an abrupt fall in bankruptcy filings, which in turn accounted for a large portion of the credit card losses; the number of filings (and thus default fees) would increase again, whether or not the general conditions for borrowers were worsening.
Industry also reports solid payment rates, showing how much of their debt consumers pay off each month
and confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured finance.
