Venus is the Earth's infernal twin
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: The European space probe "Venus Express" has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles, as they also occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that it flashes on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the proof - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning on Venus shoots at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "primordial soup theory", lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean, which led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: “If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is around a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be Earth’s devil twin, but it’s a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has taken such a completely different development is the basic question of the ESA mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, since since the beginning of the nineties no probe was on the way specifically for the exploration of this planet.
According to the researchers, the latest research results, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underscore the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities between our neighbouring planet and Earth are greater than initially assumed," the ESA said.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents on the terrestrial winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it revolves much more slowly around itself: A Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus barely resembles Earth with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets originated under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained in oceans on Earth, but on which Venus was lost in space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed in carbonate rocks on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
