These aren't Warhol's boxes.
If you combine the terms Sweden and wooden box, think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Is it?
Currently, wooden boxes manufactured in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol’s catalogue of works.
A large part of the ninety-four "Stockholm-type" brillo boxes listed there are forgeries.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's brillo boxes of 1968, internal investigations in the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now come to a sobering result: The six "brillo boxes" that the former museum director Pontus Hultén on the international Umslauf bequeathed to the Moderna Museet in 1995 are also copies of the Brillo.
The prehistory is interwoven, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of cardboard Brillo boxes: these did not come from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not about works of art, but about their role models, about mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, which, however, were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at that time were the authorized original Andy Warhol brillo boxes with the name "type Stockholm" and rightly entered the history of art and auctions.
Some of them have made more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, examined the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, as well as three privately owned ones, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their chipboards were first primed and sanded, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the chipboard with a paint roller without a primer - moreover, it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's brillo boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet, "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
However, back in July, the Authentication Board announced it was investigating the “serious allegations” made in the case of soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, they have been shrouded in unrelenting silence.
Rebel soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers have given up hiding in a hotel in Manila, demanding the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He could not be responsible for bloodshed, said the leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and election fraud, reporters at the hotel.
Government loyal soldiers had previously stormed the hotel under tear gas.
The approximately two dozen soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
Around half of them were on trial on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly settle down with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police officers who were supposed to guard him had apparently defected to him and joined his mutiny.
They invaded the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government forces closed off the district around the noble hotel.
The President called an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Advisor Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
“People have had enough,” Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who previously commanded the Scout Rangers’ elite unit, said other army units wanted to join the march soon.
Government critics had called for large demonstrations against the president for Friday.
Your government has been overshadowed by corruption allegations for months.
